      <Placemark>
        <name>Pilton</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4jT3b2ljD9TT8N3Pz17Lil7c5PSAMpQWSL43TPFJdlXqbIQOb5D17HemuBuV4OqZhiWZGU3KNBGTjxeU7Ug-UC3wqP4zj75dUIWMIUMAZeLUuC" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>In the twelfth century, Pilton was run directly by Glastonbury Abbey and was a powerful centre in its own right. The Abbot of Glastonbury had a palace here, on the site of the present manor house. Legend says that Pilton church was founded by Joseph of Arimathea who built a wattle and daub church where babtisms might take place. The church is dedicated to John the Baptist and the Tithe chest in the church contains rare leather bound books that were hidden during the dissolution when Glastonbury's famous library was destroyed. On the church tower are the recurrent symbols of the Lamb of God and the Phoenix rising triumphantly from its flaming pyre, a potent image of transformation and rebirth.<br><br><img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4gj79XRN5tHcQvtJYIaTTx0MK5IWJilKTDGHgxGX9nEz3OpbP-hJIX9ZnNwjHuaCCcb4_hlplYkcL_1m96-mzeINKEUenAz380oVCH9LbZ" height="200" width="auto" />]]></description>
