      <Placemark>
        <name>Silbury Hill</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5mUbA0w9HiwMsQ76-QqEMnCsJYFtTGkIWrWtFe6huP0ahm19x1By82cf39YNwuieBQsDsnINqhc8FF-kymqmySuKqBG-7UX4nw0p6O_Tppeg" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>One theory is that the hill was constructed as a signal beacon. The summit is perfectly in line of site from the Sanctuary and from Knoll Clump (the head and tail of the sacred landscape) and so a beacon lit here would signal a ceremonial procession along the megalithic avenue to the main henge complex of Avebury.]]></description>
