      <Placemark>
        <name>Bury St Edmunds Abbey</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6MFxnxJ9zW15ljDAHLozbKLFaGRCXmF29dtORdK94e9KeD49tKf9SD_1FiEGpAt90fkVGApvwzAixyMvjOu-y6gs8jeVoIKVhaElSJQgBBwaQkUONfLhCa" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>The Abbey of Bury St Edmunds was once among the richest Benedictine monasteries in England. Its Abbots went to extraordinary lengths to enlarge their collections of holy relics and pilgrims, royal , noble, ecclesiastical and common brought such treasures with them that the shrine within the heart of the abbey glittered with gold, jewels and all manner of precious artefacts. -  until the Dissolution of the monasteries in 1539. In the early 10th century, the relics of the martyred king, St Edmund, were tranferred from Hoxne to Beodricsworth, afterwards known as St. Edmundsbury, the site had already been in religious use for nearly three centuries]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-503-DB4436-labelson</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
          <Data name="gx_media_links">
            <value>https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6MFxnxJ9zW15ljDAHLozbKLFaGRCXmF29dtORdK94e9KeD49tKf9SD_1FiEGpAt90fkVGApvwzAixyMvjOu-y6gs8jeVoIKVhaElSJQgBBwaQkUONfLhCa</value>
          </Data>
        </ExtendedData>
