        </Point>
      </Placemark>
      <Placemark>
        <name>Hoxne</name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v4xn4u0h9VP3ZViASfBXYu4MwndKZZSfs1ji-UWmC0hO0KiIBfJdpgML0XDz-3R8bJ7RlqeTdKhEz1Djh1NAAlEB2xC8BsdsnEG5HBjpYebFxeS4mY" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>This is the legendary place of the death of Saxon King Edmund. crowned in 855 he was a revered monarch. His East Anglian kingdom was devastated by the Danish marauders who defeated him in 869. He sought refuge in Hoxne, then an important town with a cathedral. Edmunds head was cut off but went missing and was later found being guarded by a wolf in the forest who willingly gave it up and followed the procession back to Hoxne for the burial in the Kings grave. Later the remains were disinterred and reburied at Beodericsworth, which became Bury St Edmunds. St Edmund became one of the most notable saints in England. he is associated in 11th and 12th centuries with St Michael. ]]></description>
        <styleUrl>#icon-503-DB4436-labelson</styleUrl>
        <ExtendedData>
