      <Placemark>
        <name><![CDATA[St Margaret's Hopton-on-Sea]]></name>
        <description><![CDATA[<img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v6KOkDoGM-6_SP1vNWx6lR6q9hyhD40KVydNy6Y0yOhHvoKmWGvBMHGn5gW3G7eOdqnISy1Zu18cuFEP4NG1x7Ax7fkLOP1iAXZsgBCXfUlpo-Caf8unCtllvANbv4C3PlVgHI05z6mZxN_" height="200" width="auto" /><br><br>Destroyed by fire in January 1865 when a gale fanned an over -heated stove in to  fierce fire. The heat peeled off dozens of coats of whitewash to reveal brilliantly coloured patterns, which can still be faintly seen. Some of the material from which St Margaret's was built came from another church in Newton, before it disappeared beneath the sea.<br><br><img src="https://lh3.googleusercontent.com/umsh/AN6v0v5Ue35q_Zy0F5MKdR6XFBNjy08xpaux5caxpvjUloNm_xxoo53VAPNJ_OoEAAVcLm-72JjsSdr5k_S3xtqRMXyLWe883osel5iVN0h850n2JtD64LQa3gKQ9uKm_1HZgH0QxlyCug" height="200" width="auto" />]]></description>
